Consider the following four probability density functions (pdf):

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{Math_Exam_Resources_Courses_MATH103_April_2011_Question_1_(b)_image_1.png}
\caption{Math\_Exam\_Resources\_Courses\_MATH103\_April\_2011\_Question\_1\_(b)\_image\_1.png}
\end{figure}

\begin{longtable}[c]{@{}ll@{}}
\textbf{\emph{i.}} & Which pdf has the smallest mean?\\
\textbf{\emph{ii.}} & Which pdf has the largest variance?\\
\textbf{\emph{iii.}} & Which pdf has the smallest standard deviation?\\
\textbf{\emph{iv.}} & Which pdf has median larger than mean?\\
\textbf{\emph{v.}} & Find the maximal probability density in
(4).\\(Note: the peaks at \emph{a} and \emph{b} are of equal heights.)\\
\end{longtable}
